{"entries":[{"caption":"1000 Women Screened with VIA: Each square is one woman. Green = correct result, Red = incorrect result. Note the large number of false positives (red, bottom-right cluster) even though specificity is 85%.","key":"fig-via-icon-array","order":{"number":1,"section":[6,3,3,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Standard 2×2 Table Layout: Index Test in Rows, Gold Standard in Columns","key":"tbl-2x2-layout","order":{"number":1,"section":[6,3,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Pre-Test to Post-Test Probability for VIA and Pap Smear. Red lines = after positive test; Blue lines = after negative test. Pap’s positive result (LR+ = 12) shifts probability more dramatically than VIA’s (LR+ = 5.3).","key":"fig-fagan-via-pap","order":{"number":4,"section":[6,7,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The Two-Step Diagnostic Strategy: Screen with a sensitive test, then confirm with a specific test. This approach maximises detection while minimising unnecessary treatment.","key":"fig-two-step-strategy","order":{"number":7,"section":[6,9,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The ‘See and Treat’ Model: VIA’s strength is not in PPV — it’s in the ability to immediately treat positives with cryotherapy on the same visit, preventing loss to follow-up.","key":"fig-via-see-treat","order":{"number":10,"section":[6,10,3,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"AUC Interpretation Scale","key":"tbl-auc-interpretation","order":{"number":5,"section":[6,8,3,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Malaria RDT: Same test, different seasons, dramatically different PPV. During monsoon (25% prevalence), PPV = 85% — highly useful. During dry season (2%), PPV drops to 26% — most positives are false alarms.","key":"fig-malaria-season","order":{"number":9,"section":[6,10,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"PPV vs Prevalence for VIA and Pap Smear. At low prevalence (screening camps), both tests have low PPV — but Pap’s higher specificity gives it an advantage. At higher prevalence (referral clinics), both perform well.","key":"fig-ppv-prevalence-via-pap","order":{"number":3,"section":[6,5,4,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Two-Step Diagnostic Pathways Used in Indian Public Health","key":"tbl-two-step-india","order":{"number":7,"section":[6,9,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"2×2 Table: VIA Screening for Cervical Precancer (n = 1000, Prevalence = 5%)","key":"tbl-2x2-via","order":{"number":2,"section":[6,3,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Likelihood Ratio Interpretation Scale","key":"tbl-lr-interpretation","order":{"number":4,"section":[6,6,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Head-to-Head: VIA vs Pap Smear at 5% Prevalence","key":"tbl-via-pap-comparison","order":{"number":3,"section":[6,5,3,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"When to Prioritise Sensitivity vs Specificity","key":"tbl-test-selection","order":{"number":6,"section":[6,9,0,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"GeneXpert for TB: Excellent discrimination. At 3% prevalence, PPV = 75% and NPV = 99.9%. This is what happens when you have very high specificity — PPV stays useful even at low prevalence.","key":"fig-tb-scenario","order":{"number":8,"section":[6,10,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"VIA vs Pap Smear: A Trade-Off. VIA catches more cases (higher sensitivity) but produces more false alarms (lower specificity). Pap misses more cases but has fewer false alarms.","key":"fig-via-vs-pap","order":{"number":2,"section":[6,4,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"ROC Curve for Fasting Blood Glucose as a Diabetes Screening Test. Each point is a different cutoff value. The curve shows the trade-off: lowering the cutoff catches more diabetics (higher sensitivity) but also more false positives (lower specificity).","key":"fig-roc-glucose","order":{"number":5,"section":[6,8,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Comparing Two Diagnostic Tests by ROC Curves. The curve closer to the top-left corner is the better test. The difference in AUC quantifies how much better.","key":"fig-roc-comparison","order":{"number":6,"section":[6,8,4,0,0,0,0]}}],"headings":["learning-objectives","real-world-dilemma-cervical-cancer-screening-in-rural-india","part-1-the-22-contingency-table","the-standard-layout","work